occupy as much of the same territory, but we welcome you back to Tennessee

02:16.000 --> 02:18.000
whenever you can come.

02:18.000 --> 02:19.000
Thank you, sir.

02:19.000 --> 02:24.000
And Colonel Marshall, tell us something about the Tom Bigby Waterway.

02:24.000 --> 02:33.000
Show us where it starts and where it goes to and a little bit about the history of it if you would.

02:33.000 --> 02:40.000
Well, sir, the Tennessee Tom Bigby is known now as designed to connect the Tom Bigby River

02:40.000 --> 02:43.000
with the Tennessee River.

02:43.000 --> 02:47.000
This route has been considered for many years.

02:47.000 --> 02:52.000
The early French settlers looked at the divide just below the Tennessee

02:52.000 --> 02:58.000
and hoped to build a canal to the south in order to connect the Tennessee River with the Gulf.

02:58.000 --> 03:02.000
Now, the Tom Bigby River comes up to about where this arrow is.

03:02.000 --> 03:03.000
Is that correct?

03:03.000 --> 03:04.000
Yes, sir.

03:04.000 --> 03:10.000
The natural stream terminates it about this area and then we would go into a canal type operation.

03:10.000 --> 03:15.000
As I recall back in the 1870s, the Corps of Engineers actually recommended the building

03:15.000 --> 03:20.000
of a Charlotte Channel connecting the Gulf with the Tennessee River.

03:20.000 --> 03:21.000
Yes, sir.

03:21.000 --> 03:28.000
In 1875, the Corps of Engineers rendered a report to the Congress indicating that a four foot channel

03:28.000 --> 03:36.000
could be constructed essentially along this alignment at the cost of them as only $1,700,000.

03:36.000 --> 03:38.000
Yes, sir.

03:39.000 --> 03:45.000
Another pick-up deck was built here, I believe, about 1935 or six.

03:45.000 --> 03:46.000
Yes, sir.

03:46.000 --> 03:55.000
And that is toward the Chattanooga from the, where the canal, where the waterway would enter.

03:55.000 --> 04:00.000
And with that high water that does make it possible for water to come down to the ten locks

04:00.000 --> 04:04.000
of the Tennessee Tom Bigby waterway.

04:04.000 --> 04:05.000
Yes, sir.

04:05.000 --> 04:11.000
Just like Gattu and the Lake on the top of Panama Canal, it makes it possible.

04:11.000 --> 04:12.000
Yes, sir.

04:12.000 --> 04:17.000
The fact that Pickwick Pool is available and has an adequate supply of water which could be

04:17.000 --> 04:22.000
diverted to the canal will permit the operation of these various locks.

04:22.000 --> 04:25.000
And in fact makes it canal much more feasible.

04:25.000 --> 04:32.000
I was in the House of Representatives at the time back in 1946 when the Tennessee Tom Bigby

04:33.000 --> 04:36.000
was approved by the Congress in that year.

04:36.000 --> 04:44.000
And then I believe that there was some restudy, a preparation for a restudy of 1956 or if the

04:44.000 --> 04:48.000
engineers didn't make a restudy about that time.

04:48.000 --> 04:49.000
That's correct, sir.

04:49.000 --> 04:55.000
There was some debate and perhaps some doubts regarding the economic aspect of the project.

04:55.000 --> 05:01.000
And so we were directed to undertake a restudy of the economics which we have recently finished.

05:02.000 --> 05:07.000
And what is the report, the economics of this great development?

05:07.000 --> 05:13.000
Well, fundamentally, as in all our projects, the determination was made of the total cost

05:13.000 --> 05:14.000
of the project.

05:14.000 --> 05:19.000
It's about $250 million, a little more than that.

05:19.000 --> 05:26.000
And then based on the 50-year, expected at least 50-year, expected economic life of the project,

05:27.000 --> 05:29.000
an annual cost was determined.

05:29.000 --> 05:38.000
An annual cost of about $12 million and compared to that annual cost, an annual benefit was also determined.

05:38.000 --> 05:46.000
And we then found that the benefit exceeded the cost and therefore that it was in fact an economically justifiable project.

05:46.000 --> 05:53.000
And how much traffic on the waterway view in this state will be the average over a period of 50 years?

05:54.000 --> 05:58.000
About $12 million, a little over $12 million per year, sir.

05:58.000 --> 06:04.000
Now the details as I understand that how deep will the waterway be?

06:04.000 --> 06:09.000
It will be a nine-foot project initially throughout its length.

06:09.000 --> 06:16.000
In constructing the 10 locks which you mentioned earlier, we will provide for 13 foot depths

06:16.000 --> 06:23.000
in the later life of the project traffic warrant construction to that added depth.

06:23.000 --> 06:33.000
But fundamentally it will provide for a nine-foot navigable waterway, a varying widths 150 feet in some sections and wider in others.

06:33.000 --> 06:45.000
Yes, but eventually if it needed to be done, it could be a 13 foot depth and the blocks will be built so as to accommodate traffic with 13 foot depths.

06:45.000 --> 06:56.000
Then we will have a slack waterway from the Oehaw River near Perduca.

06:56.000 --> 07:05.000
Of course this is the Tennessee Lake, sometimes it's called the Kentucky Lake but related part in Tennessee is a slack water lake.

07:05.000 --> 07:16.000
And then the slack water all the way down to the go so that the barges and ships can go either way to the Oehaw in slack waters that...

07:16.000 --> 07:18.000
That's fundamentally correct, yes.

07:18.000 --> 07:25.000
If they want to go up the Tennessee to Knoxville, the water, of course the river is navigable and the water is comparatively slack.

07:26.000 --> 07:40.000
Then of course there is a canal between the Kentucky Lake and the Cumberland Barclay Lake on the Cumberland River which will make it available for traffic on the Cumberland.

07:40.000 --> 07:49.000
Now what will be shipped down the canal largely and figuratively economic benefits, Colonel Marshall?

07:50.000 --> 07:59.000
